## Reproducing our results

The Alice and Bob datasets are not included in this repo (provided by the sponsor).
To reproduce our experiments:

1. Place the sponsor-provided Alice and Bob files in `/data`.
2. Open `PPRL.ipynb`. Each experiment was run manually: set the epsilon value (2, 3 or 4)
   and select the Alice/Bob file near the top of the notebook, then Run All.
3. Blocking configurations tested: [2], [4] and [2,4].
4. The pipeline encodes the quasi-identifiers into Bloom filters (and Counting Bloom
   Filters), applies differential privacy by bit-flipping at the chosen epsilon, blocks
   records, then classifies each record pair as match / non-match using the five models
   (threshold baseline, Logistic Regression, Random Forest, SVM, KNN).
5. F1, precision and recall are recorded per model for each dataset × epsilon × blocking
   combination, and compiled into our results sheet and final report.
6. Each configuration was run once per setting. [If your notebook splits train/test for the
   ML models with a random_state, add it here so results match exactly.]
## Key results
- ML models (especially SVM and Random Forest) were more resilient to DP noise and data
  corruption than the threshold baseline.
- Best model: SVM (~0.97 F1). Recommended epsilon 3–4 and Counting Bloom Filter encoding.

